Cite your sources with links.

40 Levels:  ... Year/Month: 2015
  1. What does ICD stand for? Which version is used for this particular dataset? Name five other countries that use the ICD for official mortality data.

ICD is an acronym for International Classification Of Diseases. (inside the data) This version is Underlying Cause of Death 1999-2016, specifically 2015, for all states in U.S. (inside the data) Belgium, Denmark, Canada, China, France. (https://www.cdc.gov/globalhealth/countries/default.htm)

  1. Which U.S. organizations collects mortality data? Where is the headquarters located?

NCHS Organization (https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/about/index.htm) Headquarters Hyattsville, MD (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Center_for_Health_Statistics)

  1. In brief, how is the data collected? What is the estimated accuracy rate, according to the dataset documentation?

Data is collected via surveys, personal interviews in households, by phone, from other agencies and private partners. (wikipedia and https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/factsheets/factsheet_health_statistics.htm) The NCHS mainly goes over their data gathering process. they do not mention the estimated accuracy rate. Accuracy is at a global level of satisfaction, but it is not explicitely mentioned. (https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/factsheets/factsheet_nhis.htm)

Explore length vs. year in the ggplot2movies dataset, after removing outliers. (Choose a reasonable cutoff).

Draw four scatterplots of length vs. year from the with the following variations:

  1. Points with alpha blending
# install.packages("ggplot2movies")
# library(ggplot2movies)
dataf <- subset(ggplot2movies::movies, length < 200)
ggplot(dataf, aes(x=length, y=year))+
  geom_point(alpha=.1)

  1. Points with alpha blending + density estimate contour lines
ggplot(dataf, aes(x=length, y=year))+
  geom_point(alpha=.1)+
  geom_density2d(bins=22)

  1. Hexagonal heatmap of bin counts
ggplot(dataf, aes(x=length, y=year))+
  geom_hex(bin=10)

  1. Square heatmap of bin counts
ggplot(dataf, aes(length, year, fill=length)) +
  geom_tile() +
  coord_equal()

  1. Describe noteworthy features of the data, using the movie ratings example on page 82 (last page of Section 5.3) as a guide.
  1. there is no data for movies made before 1890
  2. 1950 saw a trend where movies branched off to either be less than 25 minutes or between 50-125 minutes in length
  3. around the 1980 time movies tended to be longer in time and the shorter time type movie decreased in frequency, until resurging back in popularity at around 1990-2000
  4. there is a hole in the data where very few films are length ~20-50
  5. all films were very short in length until around 1915
  1. How do (a)-(d) compare? Are there features that you can see in some but not all of the graphs?
  1. clearly the contour lines using geom_density add clarity to the true nature of the frequency between graphs a and b.
  2. the geom_hex graph also clearly shows the frequency/count, and even more closely, as it adds in color concentration to make it more evident
  3. the geom_tile in d makes it nice to see how many movies of a certain length merge together, since the square nature of the tiles can also help to show frequency, to some degree
